  "prompt": "Why didn't Balram (brother of Krishna) participate in the Mahabharat War?",
  "response": "Balram, the elder brother of Krishna, did not participate in the Mahabharata War due to several reasons rooted in his personal relationships and principles. Here are the key factors:\n\n1. **Neutrality and Affection for Both Sides**: Balram had deep affection for both the Pandavas and the Kauravas. He had taught mace fighting to both Bhima (from the Pandavas) and Duryodhana (from the Kauravas). His close relationships with key figures on both sides made it difficult for him to take sides in the conflict.\n\n2. **Dislike for Warfare**: Balram was known for his peaceful nature and his dislike for unnecessary violence. He believed that the war was avoidable and was disappointed with the failure of negotiations that could have prevented it.\n\n3. **Pilgrimage**: During the time of the Mahabharata War, Balram chose to go on a pilgrimage along the banks of the river Saraswati. This decision allowed him to stay away from the battlefield and maintain his neutrality.\n\n4. **Krishna's Role**: Balram was aware of Krishna's divine plan and his role in the epic. He respected Krishna's decisions and chose not to interfere, understanding that Krishna's actions were part of a larger cosmic scheme.\n\nBy staying out of the war, Balram adhered to his principles of neutrality and non-violence, while also avoiding the painful choice of having to fight against his beloved students and relatives.",
